{"aid": "40034207", "title": "Squatters take over Gordon Ramsey's restaurant", "url": "https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-london-68806116", "domain": "bbc.com", "votes": 19, "user": "darth_avocado", "posted_at": "2024-04-14 20:31:28", "comments": 5, "source_title": "Squatters take over Gordon Ramsay's \u00a313m London pub", "source_text": "Squatters take over Gordon Ramsay's \u00a313m London pub\n\n# Squatters take over Gordon Ramsay's \u00a313m London pub\n\n1 day ago\n\nAlison Earle/BBC\n\nA group advertising the space on Instagram claims it is being used as a\ncommunity space\n\nSquatters have taken over a pub owned by Gordon Ramsay in central London,\nwhich is currently up for sale with a guide price of \u00a313m.\n\nThe group of at least six people have boarded up windows and put up a \"legal\nwarning\" defending their occupation of the Grade II-listed York & Albany hotel\nand gastropub near Regent's Park.\n\nThe BBC understands they want to use the space as a community art cafe.\n\nGordon Ramsay Restaurants has been contacted for comment by the BBC.\n\nBBC reporter Alison Earle, who is at the scene, said a notice asking for food\nand donations had been ripped down.\n\nTwo accounts on Instagram called the Camden Art Cafe and Autonomous Winter\nShelter have posted about a \"new squatted community space\" at the York &\nAlbany hotel.\n\nPhotos appear to show part of the interior of the pub set up with tables.\n\nPolice were called to the pub but did not attend, saying it was a \"civil\nmatter\"\n\nThe Met said it had been called but it was a \"civil matter\".\n\nIn photographs taken before the windows had been further boarded up, a\nsquatter could be seen sleeping on a sofa in the bar surrounded by litter, The\nSun has reported.\n\nOn Saturday morning, two masked squatters wearing black tracksuits and\ncarrying backpacks and carrier bags left the property, avoiding journalists,\nthe Press Association reported.\n\nPA Media\n\nA notice taped to a door said the group had a right to occupy the venue, which\nthey said was not a \"residential building\" and was therefore not subject to\n2012 legislation which bans squatting in a residential building.\n\nSigned by \"The Occupiers\", the notice said there was always \"at least one\nperson in occupation\" and claimed any attempt to enter the premises without\ntheir permission was a criminal offence and could result in a prison sentence\nor fine.\n\n\"If you want to get us out you will have to issue a claim for possession in\nthe county court or in the High Court,\" the note added.\n\nOccupation of a person's non-residential property without their permission is\nnot itself a crime in the UK, though police can take action if crimes are\nsubsequently committed, including damaging the property.\n\nIn a statement, the Metropolitan Police said it was made aware of squatters on\n10 April.\n\n\"This is a civil matter and so police did not attend the property,\" the force\nadded.\n\nAccording to government guidance, squatters can apply to become the registered\nowners of a property if they have occupied it continuously for 10 years, acted\nas owners for the whole of that time and had not previously been given\npermission to live there by the owner.\n\nPA Media\n\nThe group occupying the pub has asked for donations of food, clothes or other\nunwanted items\n\nIn 2007, film director Gary Love bought the freehold of the former 19th\nCentury coaching inn and subsequently leased it to Mr Ramsay on a 25-year term\nwith an annual rent of \u00a3640,000.\n\nThe Kitchen Nightmares host unsuccessfully attempted to free himself from the\nlease in a legal battle at the High Court in 2015.\n\nThe venue went on sale at the end of last year with a guide price of \u00a313m.\n\nListen to the best of BBC Radio London on Sounds and follow BBC London on\nFacebook, X and Instagram. Send your story ideas to hello.bbclondon@bbc.co.uk\n\n## 'Stolen house' owner gets home back with squatters\n\n## The homes from '17th Century squatters' rights'\n\n## 'Why I don't want to live in a house'\n\nLondon\n\nSquatting\n\nRelated\n\n## Sunset Boulevard equals Olivier Awards record\n\n23 mins ago\n\nEntertainment & Arts\n\n## Stars hit the red carpet at Olivier Awards\n\n3 hrs ago\n\nEntertainment & Arts\n\n## Gordon Ramsay pub squatters defend occupation\n\n4 hrs ago\n\nLondon\n\nMore\n\n14 Nov 2023\n\n## Community group to be evicted after court order\n\nThe group has been holding events in an empty building, saying it is meant to\nbe for community use.\n\n14 Nov 2023\n\nGloucestershire\n\n3 Nov 2022\n\n## Boat daubed with obscene insults taken from river\n\nThe boat in Southampton, daubed with offensive slogans, is to be broken up.\n\n3 Nov 2022\n\nHampshire & Isle of Wight\n\n23 Sep 2022\n\n## River boat clearance delayed amid abuse claims\n\nBoats in Southampton are daubed with offensive slogans amid claims of\nsquatters' rights.\n\n23 Sep 2022\n\nHampshire & Isle of Wight\n\n25 Aug 2021\n\n## The hard men removing squatters in Spain\n\nSome squatters in Spain demand cash before leaving - so eviction firms have\narisen to handle the talks.\n\n25 Aug 2021\n\nStories\n\n16 Jun 2021\n\n## Berlin squat riot leaves dozens of police wounded\n\nSixty police officers are hurt as squatters riot over a planned fire\ninspection at 94 Rigaer Stra\u00dfe.\n\n16 Jun 2021\n\nEurope\n\nCopyright 2024 BBC. All rights reserved. The BBC is not responsible for the\ncontent of external sites. Read about our approach to external linking.\n\n## Let us know you agree to cookies\n\nWe use cookies to give you the best online experience.\n\nPlease let us know if you agree to all of these cookies.\n\n  * No, take me to settings\n\n", "frontpage": true}
